[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Neuroscience seems to be converging on brains without bodies from two very different sources, one of which is growing them from human stem cells into a mini brain and keeping that on life support. And the other one is extracting an adult human brain from someone who has passed and keeping that on life'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'support. Both of these serve very similar purposes, but each one has its own advantages. And you might be asking, "What about the ethics?" And we\'ll talk about it. We know about our friends the brain organoids, the tiny human brains'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'grown from stem cells. They essentially resemble a fetal brain. They have the gene expression that you would expect of their chronological age. If you keep them alive for 5 years, they have the gene expression of a 5-year-old. When brain organoids first showed up on the'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scene, people said that they didn\'t have complex brain wave. They only had delta brain waves, which are the kind that are associated with being in a coma or asleep. But as we\'ve seen them grow, they\'re getting increasingly complex. We\'ve seen them approach criticality,'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is the space between order and disorder, which is thought to be needed for intelligence and consciousness. Now, when we\'re talking about the brain organoids, one of the big issues is how complex they can get, cuz we want to have something that really looks and'

[01:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'behaves like a human brain in order to have a reasonable research subject for human trials. The BrainX system, which works for adult human brains that were once in an adult human, operates as a life support system, essentially a synthetic body. For brain organoids,'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re doing largely the same thing, except they have to grow those support structures because as it turns out, your stem cells will become whatever you want them to be. But when they\'re not in the context of an entire body, they\'re not'

[01:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to grow the correct structures. So, if you just attach vascular organoids or even a brain organoid that has vascular components and just stick it with one that doesn\'t have it, they will connect and they will support each other. Turns out there are lots of'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'functional ways to do this. And I think the reason we have not hit human trials yet is because our brain is such an intimate part of our body, and messing it up really means messing up an awful lot. But we also haven\'t found the most effective way to make and use them. The'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'concept of their suffering has been considered, and they do provide enormous scientific merit. They allow a test subject that is not an adult human being. As for whether or not they are capable of suffering, we don\'t know. They are a human brain in miniature.'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They are millimeters across. We should approach them with caution. As we make them more and more complex and more complex brain activity emerges, yeah, I think there will be a line, but since'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is entirely new technology, we haven\'t found the line yet. Interestingly, one of the things that has been solved is vascularization because early brain organoids would always suffer from hypoxia, and that'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would limit their life spans. Another issue is that they haven\'t been kept in the correct media. I mean, we are essentially floating around in cerebrospinal fluid. But they need to have a media that supports neural firing. So, neurons'

[02:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t just give up. Our brain is a dynamic system, and if it doesn\'t have things to learn or things to do, yeah, it does kind of just give up. We know we like to talk about science scandals here, too, and one scandal can set the'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'field back by decades. So, it is really important that we get this right before we start working with actual humans, and it does take a serious amount of time, especially for a system that has so much promise. Yeah, you want to make sure'

[03:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ve examined every possible method. Unlike brain in a vat, which operates primarily as a research model, brain organoids, while yes, they are also research models, have a great number of applications for medicine directly as a'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'treatment. I\'m not saying that one is more valuable than the other. Both of these systems are really cutting-edge research, but one, I think, has more direct applications for a patient. And yeah, they\'re both kind of equally'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spooky. Maybe one is more spooky than the other. I haven\'t decided which. One of the things, of the many things, I\'m very excited for with brain organoids is neural repair because they have shown promise as treatments for strokes. In fact, the only effective'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'treatment that I\'ve seen for strokes. People have been trying stem cells for a very long time, but they don\'t tend to survive. If you give them a foothold, if you let them already start to become neural tissue, they do a lot better and vascularizing them is going to make them'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more effective because that has been one of the great concerns. If you pop them in somebody\'s head and they don\'t survive, it could cause additional damage. A lot of research has been done introducing these two stroke induced'

[04:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mice and I\'ve even seen some research with Parkinson\'s induced mice. Healthy brain organoids usually made from humans, which I know is a little bit spooky, but if you were working with organoids in a medical system that eventually is going to become a human'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want to work with human things because it is more applicable. I look through the medical trial database just to see just to see if anyone has taken brain organoids yet. I\'ve seen other things with gut organoids and those are really'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'promising, but I keep an eye on it. I don\'t know if you\'re seeing what I\'m seeing, but these immunostains are absolutely gorgeous. Yes, they added fluorescence. Often times they use something called optogenetics so cells can fluoresce so they\'re easier to look'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at under a microscope and we can see what\'s actually happening. This is a promising treatment for conditions that we have never had any treatment for in all of human history. I am really excited for that despite the fact that'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yes, there are some ethical concerns about creating undue suffering. Despite the best efforts of most researchers that really do care about the ethics of these experiments, yes, there is some stuff that goes on that I'

[05:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think is a little bit questionable. Using brain organoids for computation, bio computation. Even if we have determined almost certainly there\'s no consciousness present. They\'ve not created suffering. I still have concerns'

[05:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and think that we should go in a different direction just based on the possibility that it could show up and maybe that is close-minded of me. Now, the one that I am biting at the champ to see and as soon as it turns up, I will tell you all'

[05:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'immediately is when brain organoids and brain X combine and we take a revived human brain from a human, give it something like a a and then treat it with brain organoids because right now I'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think that is very possible. Granted, at this moment this is brand new technology and researchers have not been keeping brains alive for very long in a vat. Usually they keep them for about a day, but they are looking to'

[05:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'extend that to weeks and possibly longer. And I should say because people are concerned, no there is no evidence that the brain in a vat is conscious or experiencing any kind of consciousness. Yes, consciousness is poorly defined,'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but we have a pretty good idea of what somebody looks like when they\'re in a coma. This is essentially the lowest level of brain activity. Yes, the cells are technically still alive in a failing system. They also have them under heavy'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sedation just in case. Just on the weird possibility that there is any consciousness present, they make sure that they would not suffer. And that does not bring as much comfort as maybe it should,'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but if it gets unethical, I will let you know because I love to talk about that kind of stuff. I hope you\'ve enjoyed this. Follow for more.'
